'''Dr. Angus Morris "Monk" McDonald''' (February 21, 1901<U+2013>September 2, 1977) was an American [[college athletics|college athlete]], a [[List of North Carolina Tar Heels men's head basketball coaches|head coach]] for the [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team]], and a [[urologist]].  He is best known for his time as an college athlete playing [[American football|football]], [[college basketball|basketball]], and [[college baseball|baseball]] for the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], and is generally considered the best all-around college athlete to attend the University of North Carolina.<ref name='Star News'> {{cite news | title = Hall of Fame Tickets are available | date = 1977-02-13 | publisher = Star News | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4LgsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HRMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3081,2315526&dq=monk-mcdonald&hl=en | work = The Sunday Star News | pages = 12C | accessdate = 2010-11-06}}</ref> For his collegiate and coaching career, he was inducted in the [[List of members of the North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame|North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame]].<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/>
 
==Early Years==
Monk McDonald was born as Angus Morris McDonald on February 21, 1901, in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] to Angus Morris, Sr. and Ann Howard McDonald.<ref name='Dictionary'> {{cite book | last1 = Powell | first1 = William | title = Dictionary of North Carolina biography | volume = 4 | publisher = The University of North Carolina Press | date = 31 Mar 1991 | year = 1991 | pages = 136 | url = http://books.google.com/books?ei=reHTTNu7KcSBlAet_rTQBA&ct=result&id=ofYTiRPm6zoC&dq=Dr.+Angus+%22Monk%22+McDonald+north+carolina+hall+of+fame+1901+1977&q=McDonald+1901+1977#v=snippet&q=McDonald%201901%201977&f=false | accessdate = 2010-11-10 | isbn = 0807819182 }}</ref> Monk McDonald's father, Angus Morris Sr., was the founder of the Southern Real Estate Company and was a chairman on the [[Mecklenburg County, North Carolina|Mecklenburg County]] [[Board of Commissioners]].<ref name='Dictionary'/> McDonald attended [[Garinger High School|Charlotte High School]] and [[Fishburne Military School]] before attending the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/>

==College== 
While at North Carolina, McDonald, who was 5 feet, 7 inches, played [[quarterback]] on the [[American football|football team]], [[Basketball position#Backcourt (guards)|guard]] on the [[college basketball|men's basketball team]], and [[shortstop]] on the [[college baseball|baseball team]].<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/>  McDonald [[Varsity letter|lettered]] in all three sports for all four years.<ref name='Dictionary'/>  He is generally considered the best all-around athlete in North Carolina sports history.<ref name='Star News'> {{cite news | title = Hall of Fame Tickets are available | date = 1977-02-13 | publisher = Star News | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4LgsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HRMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3081,2315526&dq=monk-mcdonald&hl=en | work = The Sunday Star News | pages = 12C | accessdate = 2010-11-06}}</ref> 

McDonald also won the first Patterson Medal, the most prestigious award for student-athletes at the University of North Carolina, for his collegiate career in 1924.<ref name="Patterson"/>

===Football and baseball===
McDonald [[Varsity letter|lettered]] in football for the four years that he attended North Carolina.<ref name="North Carolina Football p=151">{{harvnb|2009 North Carolina Football Media Guide|2009|p=151}}</ref> McDonald most successful season in football came in 1922 when, as quarterback, he led North Carolina to a 9<U+2013>1 record and led North Carolina to a first place standing in the [[Southern Conference]].<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/><ref name="North Carolina Football p=189">{{harvnb|2009 North Carolina Football Media Guide|2009|p=189}}</ref>  During one game that season, McDonald had a [[kickoff (American football)|kickoff return]] of 95 [[yards]] against [[Carolina <U+2013> NC State rivalry|in-state rival]] [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]], which is the ninth longest kickoff return in North Carolina football history.<ref name="North Carolina Football p=179">{{harvnb|2009 North Carolina Football Media Guide|2009|p=179}}</ref>

During his baseball career, McDonald [[batting average|batted]] over .300 and helped his team to 19 wins and only two losses during the 1922 season.<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/>  McDonald was good enough to be considered a prospective professional baseball player.<ref name='Dictionary'/>

===Basketball===
McDonald first played on North Carolina under head coach [[Fred Boye]] for the 1920<U+2013>21 season, and during this season, North Carolina earned a 12<U+2013>8 record. After the 1920<U+2013>21 season, were without a head coach for two years after Boye left the team.<ref name="Rappoport 2002 p=14-15">{{harvnb|Rappoport|2002|pp=14<U+2013>15}}</ref>

During the 1921<U+2013>22 season, North Carolina played its first season in the [[Southern Conference]], gained a 15<U+2013>6 record, and won the first [[List of Southern Conference men's basketball champions|Southern Conference Tournament]].  McDonald was named all-Southern Conference&mdash;an award given annually to the best basketball players during the regular season in the Southern Conference division&mdash;at the end of this season.<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/><ref name="North Carolina p=174">{{harvnb|2009<U+2013>10 Basketball Carolina Tar Heels Media Guide|2009|p=174}}</ref> McDonald was captain of North Carolina during the 1922<U+2013>23 season, and he lead the coachless team to a 15<U+2013>1 record, which tied North Carolina for first place in the Southern Conference regular season standings.<ref name="Rappoport 2002 p=14-15">{{harvnb|Rappoport|2002|pp=14<U+2013>15}}</ref><ref name="Rappoport 2002 p=12">{{harvnb|Rappoport|2002|p=12}}</ref> 

Before the start of the 1923<U+2013>24 season, [[Norman Shepard]] became the head coach of North Carolina.  Beside McDonald, there were several other talented players on the 1923<U+2013>24 team, including senior [[Cartwright Carmichael]], who was the first North Carolina All-American in any sport, and [[Jack Cobb]], who would later be named to the All-American team and would later have his [[Honored North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball players|number retired at North Carolina]].<ref name="Rappoport 2002 p=9, 11">{{harvnb|Rappoport|2002|pp=9, 11}}</ref>  This team earned the nickname the "White Phantoms" because of their fast playmaking and defense.<ref name="Powell 2002 p=16">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=16}}</ref>  McDonald was named all-Southern Conference and all-Southern Conference Tournament team <U+2013> an award given annually to the best players in the Southern Conference basketball tournament <U+2013> for his play during the 1923<U+2013>24 season.<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/><ref name="North Carolina p=174">{{harvnb|2009<U+2013>10 Basketball Carolina Tar Heels Media Guide|2009|p=174}}</ref> The 1923<U+2013>24 North Carolina team managed to win all 26 games they played that year.<ref name="Powell 2002 p=16">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=16}}</ref> Because there was no national post-season tournament, the final game for North Carolina was in the Southern Conference tournament against the [[Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball|University of Alabama Crimson Tide]].<ref name="Powell 2002 p=16">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=16}}</ref>  North Carolina managed to win the game 26<U+2013>18.<ref name="Powell 2002 p=16">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=16}}</ref>  The local news reported that hundreds of students at North Carolina "waited in the streets in front of telegraph offices and cafes" for news about the game and after the victory students "went wild" and set a [[bonfire]] on the athletic field.<ref name="Powell 2002 p=16">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=16}}</ref> In 1936, the [[Helms Athletic Foundation]] retroactively awarded a national championship to the 1923<U+2013>24 North Carolina men's basketball team since there had been no organization to award national championships at the time.<ref name="Powell 2002 p=16">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=16}}</ref>  This was the first national championship given to a North Carolina men's basketball team.

==Coaching at North Carolina==
After coaching North Carolina for one season, Norman Shepard went to the [[Far East]] to work as a sales manager for [[Liggett Group|Liggett and Meyer tobacco company]], which left the position of head coach open.<ref name="Rappoport 2002 p=13">{{harvnb|Rappoport|2002|p=13}}</ref> Even though McDonald has just graduated from North Carolina and had started to attend medical school full-time, he became the next head coach after Shepard's departure.<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/> McDonald was the first former player to become head coach of the North Carolina men's basketball team; [[Matt Doherty (basketball)|Matt Doherty]] would be the second.<ref name='Doherty'>{{cite news | first=Marc | last=Lancaster | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Settling in: Doherty getting a feel for his new job, wardrobe | year=2001 | publisher=CNNSI.com | url =http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/basketball/college/news/2000/07/19/doherty_peachjam/#more | work =CNNSI.com | pages = | accessdate = 2009-12-07 | language = }}</ref> 

When McDonald took over, there were still many seasoned veterans on the team including Jack Cobb.<ref name="Powell 2002 p=17">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=17}}</ref> McDonald continued the team's winning streak from the previous season for the first eight games, but North Carolina eventually lost to the [[Harvard Crimson]] basketball team ending their 34-game winning streak.<ref name="Powell 2002 p=17">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=17}}</ref>  Although the team would lose another four games, North Carolina went through the regular season unbeaten when playing at its home arena, the [[Tin Can (basketball arena)|Tin Can]].<ref name="Powell 2002 p=17">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=17}}</ref>   That season McDonald's team also managed to win the [[Southern Conference]] regular season for the second year in a row and win the [[List of Southern Conference men's basketball champions|Southern Conference Tournament]] beating [[Tulane University]] in the finals, which McDonald did not attend due to his medical studies.<ref name='Dictionary'/><ref name="Powell 2002 p=17">{{harvnb|Powell|2002|p=17}}</ref> North Carolina would end the 1924<U+2013>25 season with a 20<U+2013>5 record.

