==Later years==
McDonald gave up coaching after one year and instead focused on attending medical school.  In 1926, McDonald trasnferred to the [[University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine]] and graduated with a [[medical degree]] in 1928.<ref name='Dictionary'/> 

After graduating from medical school, McDonald would practice as both a [[urologist]] and a [[surgeon]].<ref name='Dictionary'/>  He later worked at a variety of hospitals and clinics including the Protestant Episcopal Hospital in [[Philadelphia]], the [[Mayo Clinic]] in [[Rochester, Minnesota]], [[NewYork<U+2013>Presbyterian Hospital]], and the Vanderbilt Clinic in [[New York]].<ref name='Dictionary'/>  In 1935, McDonald moved back to North Carolina and joined the practice of Dr. Fred Patterson.<ref name='Dictionary'/>  McDonald left this practice in 1939 to help the Crowell Clinic.<ref name='Dictionary'/>  In 1942 he became [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|lieutenant commander]] in [[Medical Corps (United States Navy)|United States Naval Medical Corps]].<ref name='Dictionary'/>  He transferred to [[San Francisco]] in 1944 to work in naval hospital there.<ref name='Dictionary'/>   He was discharged from the [[United States Navy]] after [[World War II]].<ref name='Dictionary'/>  After the war, McDonald resumed a urology practice in Charlotte and worked with the Crowell Clinic until his retirement in 1969.<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/><ref name='Dictionary'/>

McDonald was inducted into the [[List of members of the North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame|North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame]] on February 17, 1977.<ref name='Star News'> {{cite news | title = Hall of Fame Tickets are available | date = 1977-02-13 | publisher = Star News | url = http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4LgsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HRMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3081,2315526&dq=monk-mcdonald&hl=en | work = The Sunday Star News | pages = 12C | accessdate = 2010-11-06}}</ref>
McDonald would die seven months after being inducted on September 2, 1977.<ref name="NC Sports Hall of Fame"/><ref name='Dictionary'/>

==Personal life==
McDonald married Mary Letitia Mebane in 1939 and had three children: Letitia, Ann, and Angus.<ref name='Dictionary'/>   All of his children graduated from the University of North Carolina.<ref name='Dictionary'/>   He is buried in Elmwood Cemetary.<ref name='Dictionary'/>

